          <span style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--accent-orange),var(--accent-amber));color:#1a1a2e;font-weight:800;font-size:0.8rem;padding:0.25rem 0.65rem;border-radius:100px;flex-shrink:0;">Q2</span>
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-weight:600;margin:0;">The Strangler Fig pattern was named after what natural phenomenon, and coined by whom?</p>
        </div>
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:0.6rem;">
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">A parasitic vine &#8212; coined by Chris Richardson</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Ship hull compartments &#8212; coined by Sam Newman</button>
          <button class="kc-opt kc-correct-ans" onclick="kcAnswer(this,true,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Tropical strangler fig trees that surround and replace a host tree &#8212; coined by Martin Fowler in 2004</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Cascading waterfalls &#8212; coined by Netflix Engineering</button>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(74,222,128,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(74,222,128,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-green);">&#10003; Correct.</strong> Fowler coined it in 2004, inspired by a strangler fig that germinates in the canopy, drops roots to the ground, and gradually surrounds and replaces the host &#8212; mirroring incremental legacy system replacement. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Martin Fowler, bliki/StranglerFigApplication (2004)</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-wrong-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(248,113,113,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-red);">&#10007; Not quite.</strong> Martin Fowler coined it in 2004, named after tropical strangler fig trees that slowly envelop and replace a host tree. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Martin Fowler, bliki/StranglerFigApplication (2004)</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card kc-q" data-answered="false">
        <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.75rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <span style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--accent-orange),var(--accent-amber));color:#1a1a2e;font-weight:800;font-size:0.8rem;padding:0.25rem 0.65rem;border-radius:100px;flex-shrink:0;">Q3</span>
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-weight:600;margin:0;">In Richardson's pattern catalog, which pattern specifically addresses managing distributed transactions across multiple microservices?</p>
        </div>
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:0.6rem;">
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation)</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Circuit Breaker</button>
          <button class="kc-opt kc-correct-ans" onclick="kcAnswer(this,true,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Saga</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Event Sourcing</button>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(74,222,128,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(74,222,128,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-green);">&#10003; Correct.</strong> The Saga pattern manages distributed transactions as a sequence of local transactions. Richardson identifies two approaches: choreography-based (events) and orchestration-based (central coordinator). <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Chris Richardson, microservices.io/patterns/data/saga.html</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-wrong-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(248,113,113,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-red);">&#10007; Not quite.</strong> The Saga pattern handles distributed transactions. CQRS separates reads from writes; Circuit Breaker prevents cascading failures; Event Sourcing persists state as events. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Chris Richardson, microservices.io/patterns/data/saga.html</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card kc-q" data-answered="false">
        <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.75rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <span style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--accent-orange),var(--accent-amber));color:#1a1a2e;font-weight:800;font-size:0.8rem;padding:0.25rem 0.65rem;border-radius:100px;flex-shrink:0;">Q4</span>
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-weight:600;margin:0;">The Twelve-Factor App methodology was developed by engineers at which company, and roughly when?</p>
        </div>
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:0.6rem;">
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Netflix Engineering &#8212; circa 2013</button>
          <button class="kc-opt kc-correct-ans" onclick="kcAnswer(this,true,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Heroku (Adam Wiggins et al.) &#8212; circa 2011</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Amazon Web Services &#8212; circa 2009</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Google SRE team &#8212; circa 2014</button>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(74,222,128,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(74,222,128,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-green);">&#10003; Correct.</strong> Adam Wiggins and Heroku engineers published it circa 2011, distilling lessons from running thousands of SaaS apps on Heroku's PaaS platform into 12 factors for cloud-native SaaS design. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Adam Wiggins, 12factor.net (2011)</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-wrong-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(248,113,113,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-red);">&#10007; Not quite.</strong> Adam Wiggins and the Heroku team published the methodology circa 2011, drawn from observations of thousands of SaaS apps on their platform. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Adam Wiggins, 12factor.net (2011)</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card kc-q" data-answered="false">
        <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.75rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <span style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--accent-orange),var(--accent-amber));color:#1a1a2e;font-weight:800;font-size:0.8rem;padding:0.25rem 0.65rem;border-radius:100px;flex-shrink:0;">Q5</span>
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-weight:600;margin:0;">Conway's Law states that organizations design systems that mirror what?</p>
        </div>
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:0.6rem;">
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Their financial constraints and budget cycles</button>
          <button class="kc-opt kc-correct-ans" onclick="kcAnswer(this,true,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Their communication structures &#8212; the org chart becomes the system architecture</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">The technical stack chosen by their engineering leads</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">The regulatory environment they operate in</button>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(74,222,128,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(74,222,128,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-green);">&#10003; Correct.</strong> "Organizations which design systems are constrained to produce designs which are copies of the communication structures of these organizations." Microservices teams use the Inverse Conway Maneuver &#8212; structuring teams to match the desired architecture. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Mel Conway, Datamation (April 1968)</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-wrong-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(248,113,113,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-red);">&#10007; Not quite.</strong> Conway's Law (1968): "Organizations which design systems are constrained to produce designs which are copies of the communication structures of these organizations." <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Mel Conway, Datamation (April 1968)</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card kc-q" data-answered="false">
        <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.75rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <span style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--accent-orange),var(--accent-amber));color:#1a1a2e;font-weight:800;font-size:0.8rem;padding:0.25rem 0.65rem;border-radius:100px;flex-shrink:0;">Q6</span>
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-weight:600;margin:0;">The Bulkhead resilience pattern takes its name from which engineering domain?</p>
        </div>
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:0.6rem;">
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Aviation &#8212; compartmentalized fuel tanks on aircraft</button>
          <button class="kc-opt kc-correct-ans" onclick="kcAnswer(this,true,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Naval engineering &#8212; watertight hull compartments on ships</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Civil engineering &#8212; flood barriers and retaining walls</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Electrical engineering &#8212; fuse panels preventing overload</button>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(74,222,128,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(74,222,128,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-green);">&#10003; Correct.</strong> Named after watertight compartments in ship hulls &#8212; if one compartment floods, the others keep the ship afloat. In microservices, isolating thread pools means one slow dependency cannot exhaust all resources and bring the service down. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Michael Nygard, Release It! (2007)</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-wrong-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(248,113,113,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-red);">&#10007; Not quite.</strong> The Bulkhead pattern comes from naval engineering: watertight hull compartments prevent a single breach from sinking the vessel. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Michael Nygard, Release It! (2007)</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card kc-q" data-answered="false">
        <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.75rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <span style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--accent-orange),var(--accent-amber));color:#1a1a2e;font-weight:800;font-size:0.8rem;padding:0.25rem 0.65rem;border-radius:100px;flex-shrink:0;">Q7</span>
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-weight:600;margin:0;">In CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation), what is the fundamental separation?</p>
        </div>
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:0.6rem;">
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Separating synchronous calls from asynchronous messaging</button>
          <button class="kc-opt kc-correct-ans" onclick="kcAnswer(this,true,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Separating the write model (commands) from the read model (queries) with independent data stores</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Separating internal service calls from external API calls</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">Separating authentication logic from business logic</button>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(74,222,128,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(74,222,128,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-green);">&#10003; Correct.</strong> CQRS separates the write model (commands) from the read model (queries), each with its own optimized data store &#8212; enabling independent scaling. CQRS is often combined with Event Sourcing. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Chris Richardson, microservices.io/patterns/data/cqrs.html</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-wrong-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(248,113,113,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-red);">&#10007; Not quite.</strong> CQRS separates the write model (commands) from the read model (queries), each with its own data store for independent scaling and optimization. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Chris Richardson, microservices.io/patterns/data/cqrs.html</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card kc-q" data-answered="false">
        <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.75rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <span style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--accent-orange),var(--accent-amber));color:#1a1a2e;font-weight:800;font-size:0.8rem;padding:0.25rem 0.65rem;border-radius:100px;flex-shrink:0;">Q8</span>
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-weight:600;margin:0;">The Twelve-Factor App's "Config" principle (Factor III) specifies that application configuration should be stored where?</p>
        </div>
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:0.6rem;">
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">In a configuration file checked into the code repository</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">In a database shared across all service instances</button>
          <button class="kc-opt kc-correct-ans" onclick="kcAnswer(this,true,this.closest('.kc-q'))">In the environment &#8212; environment variables, not in code or config files</button>
          <button class="kc-opt" onclick="kcAnswer(this,false,this.closest('.kc-q'))">In the service's in-memory configuration object at startup</button>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(74,222,128,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(74,222,128,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-green);">&#10003; Correct.</strong> Factor III: "Store config in the environment." Config is anything that varies between deploys &#8212; credentials, backing service URLs, port numbers. The test: could you open-source the codebase right now without compromising credentials? <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Adam Wiggins, 12factor.net/config (2011)</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="kc-wrong-explanation" style="display:none;margin-top:1rem;padding:0.9rem 1rem;background:rgba(248,113,113,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.25);border-radius:8px;">
          <p style="color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--accent-red);">&#10007; Not quite.</strong> Factor III says config belongs in environment variables &#8212; not in code or config files in the repository, which would expose credentials and prevent portability. <em style="color:var(--text-muted);">&#8212; Adam Wiggins, 12factor.net/config (2011)</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div><!-- /questions -->
  </div>
